message.raw:
Fixed subtle bug where if a ramp on one ClockLine was segmented into three components due to constant updates on another ClockLine, and one of the ramp segments was only 1 clock_tick long, only the ramping ClockLine would tick.

The ClockLine with the constant instructions would not tick, however the IntermediateDevice was told that it did tick, and thus there was a mismatch between the number of clock ticks and the number of instructions programmed into the IntermediateDevice.

message.raw:
Fixed useless traceback when instructions exist after the experiment stop_time

If instructions existed after the experiment stop_time, then labscript would raise an unhelpful error about an index being out of range.
Instead, we now print a helpful warning indiciating there is likely a problem, and let later code take care of raising the error about instructions existing after the stop time.

message.raw:
Disabled labscript auto initialisation for the moment.
This is necessary so that things importing BLACS tabs and runviewer classes
from labscript_devices don't trigger auto initialisation.

We will probably never re-enable auto-initialisation, and will instead
make a __main__.py here so that people can still use command line compilation
of their labscripts with:

python -m labscript myfile.py my_hdf_file.h5 --options

etc.

message.raw:
Fixed bugs (now minimally tested)

* reordered classes
* fixed ramps limits not being saved in dictionary in Output class
* Fixed bug where outputs with a single update co-inciding with the start of a ramp on another clock line would both be treated as a ramp.
* fixed collect_change_times where list of unique change_times needed to be saved back into the change_times dictionary because the list pulled out of the dictionary was run through list(set()) which meant the list we were modifying was not the same one that was in the dictionary.

message.raw:
Implemented true gated clocks (untested).
labscript_devices module has not yet been updated to support this change (hence why it is untested).

* deleted slow clock
* all clock ticks are gated (not just the looping clock ticks)
* modified hierarchy of classes to be:
  - PseudoclockDevice
  --- Pseudoclock
  ----- ClockLine
  ------- IntermediateDevice
  --------- Output
* PseudoclockDevice should support multiple Pseudoclocks
* Pseudoclock should support multiple ClockLines
* ClockLines support multiple IntermediateDevices

message.raw:
Lots of refactoring of DDSs.

DDSs had many references to specific classes for their parent devices, and their behaviour was
slightly different depending on what parent device they had. This has been solved in a few ways.

For DDSs attached to a PhaseMatrixQuickSyn, there is now a subclass of DDS,
labscript_utils.PhaseMatrixQuickSyn.QuickSynDDS, which supports only frequency
control and only static gating.

For Novatechs, one should still use DDS and StaticDDS, but they call methods on
the parents asking questions about how to initialise, such as whether a certain
unit conversion class should be used if the user hasn't specified one. If the parent
does not implement this method get_default_unit_conversion_classes(), it is ignored,
so this is backward compatible.

For PulseBlasters, DDS is also still the class to use, however the creation of a
DigitalQuantity for its gating is now done in the PulseBlaster's add_device method.

In order to facilitate this, Device.__init__ now takes an argument call_parents_add_device,
which, if set to false, means Device.__init__ will not call parent_device.add_device.

This allows subclasses more control over when parent_device.add_device is called
in their own __init__ method, although it remains the case that they *must* call it
at some point in their __init__ method if they tell Device.__init__ not to.

This commit corresponds to a simultaneous one in the labscript_devices module which
implements part of this change.

message.raw:
Initial implementation (completely UNTESTED) of gated clocks

The pulseblaster should now be able to have it's fast clock duplicated across multiple flags.
Each fast clock flag can have independent sets of devices on it.
During ramps, only clock flags with ramping outputs will have the clock tick.

This, in theory, allows you to connect multiple devices to your fast clock (via different flags), but not burn instructions on devices with constant output when others are ramping.

As mentioned above, this code has never been used to compile any labscript and likely contains several bugs.
message.html:
Initial implementation (completely UNTESTED) of gated clocks

The pulseblaster should now be able to have it's fast clock duplicated across multiple flags.
Each fast clock flag can have independent sets of devices on it.
During ramps, only clock flags with ramping outputs will have the clock tick.

This, in theory, allows you to connect multiple devices to your fast clock (via different flags), but not burn instructions on devices with constant output when others are ramping.

As mentioned above, this code has never been used to compile any labscript and likely contains several bugs.

message.raw:
An attempted fix for the waits bug where absurdly short instructions were beign generated.

The fix was to round trigger times to the nearest 10ns like the rest of labscript times,
so that equality comparisons later were not subject to floating point rounding errors.

A better fix for this would be to actually subclass float myself such that all
arithmetic operations rounded, or all equality checks were in some tolerance so
we didn't have to manually pepper the code with these roundings. Or whatever.
Something to automate this.

message.raw:
Made the disabling of the fast/slow clock on the PulseBlaster more pythonic. To disable pulseblasters you now use "None" for the slow/fast clock. Apparently after 9pm my brain switches from Python to C conventions...

Refs #371

message.raw:
This commit contains barely tested code, however example.py does compile so it can't be too broken!

I have attempted to implement #371 or in other words:
* Users can chose the flags on which the slow clock and fast clock are output
* Users can choose not to output the slow or fast clock
* If no clocks are output, redundant loop instructions are not generated, thus allowing more value changes for the digital outputs and DDS channels

message.raw:
Added /devices submodule for stuff that you might not want imported all the time.

Currently used only for ADWin implementation, which is currently in a working state. ADWin has a funny implementation with its own digital and analog output objects since they are not so interchangable with other devices. Ramps are implemented by programming the device with ramp parameters, which it evaluates itself.

This required an 'Instruction' object capable of holding the ramp parameters rather than simply the function for the ramp.
